# So far, the data looks good. We have already gained some insights. 
# For example, in the first 24 hours of the data, rider numbers at night are much lower than rider numbers during the day.
# 25 percent of hours had 40 or less riders, while one hour had 866 riders.
# In terms of business, we want our hours to have a high volume of riders, and are exploring the data to figure out ways to increase ridership.
# Initial questions are how can we increase ridership? Do we run promotions when ridership is lower to promote use?
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
## Let's analyze a subset of this data 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Ridership is lower at night, so let's dive in 

# Let's look at registered riders between the hours of 2, 3, and 4 AM
print(hour.loc[2:4, 'registered'])
2    27
3    10
4     1
Name: registered, dtype: int64

# We could also use a logical condition to look at nighttime data
print(hour.loc[hour['hr']<5, 'registered'].mean())
20.7881427367238
# The logical condition "['hr']<5" selected every row in the data that had an hr variable less than 5 - this gives us a subset of data corresponding to midnight - 4 am

# We can use more complex logic to check for multiple conditions. Let's look at ridership counts on colder early mornings as compared to warmer early mornings.
print(hour.loc[(hour['hr']<5) & (hour['temp']<.50), 'cnt'].mean())
      
19.521104742053154

print(hour.loc[(hour['hr']<5) & (hour['temp']>.50), 'cnt'].mean())
      
33.639322916666664

# Ridership counts were higher between the same hours when the temperature was higher.
# We can also use an or operator | to see the ridership count if the weather is either warm or the humidity high - both don't have to be true
print(hour.loc[(hour['temp']>.50) | (hour['hum']>0.5), 'cnt'].mean())
      
193.36764103264582
# We are exploring these conditions specifically to figure out what ridership looks like when weather is uncomfortable so we can increase ridership during those instances.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
## Let's Explore the Seasonal Data 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
print(hour.groupby(['season'])['cnt'].mean())  # use the groupby() method to group by season and find the ridership mean
      
season
1    111.114569        # Season 1 is Winter
2    208.344069        # Season 2 is Spring
3    236.016237        # Season 3 is Summer
4    198.868856        # Season 4 is Fall
Name: cnt, dtype: float64

# It is already easy to tell that ridership is highest in the summer, and lowest in the winter
# We can use the groupby() method to group on multiple columns
print(hour.groupby(['season', 'holiday'])['cnt'].mean())
                    
